# Intuition

In this problem we have to find the number of paths to reach from some point ```(x1, y1)``` to some point ```(x2, y2)``` and those paths should cover all the available cell exactly one time.

Since we can move in all four directions, so we cannot apply any greedy algorithm.

So we should think about some brute-force approch which would cover all the possible paths and we will pick the valid paths.

After thinking this much, we should always think about recursion and think about implementing it with backtracking.

Note : After applying recursion, always try to think about applying Dynamic Programming to the code, in this case, it is not possible.

# Approach

So first thing we should do is to find the total number of squares which we have to visit atleast once.

And we need to find ```x1``` & ```y1``` (the starting coordinates).

Now we need to calculate the total number of paths which satisfy the above condition.

We will create a 2-d array with name ```visited``` inwhich we will mark those coordinates as true which are already being included in the path.

We will write a recursive function inwhich first we check whether we are at a valid square or not , i.e., ```row``` and ```col``` should be in the range [0, m-1] and [0, n-1] respectively.

If the square is not valid, then we return, else we will check if the square is available or not. If ```grid[row][col]``` is equal to -1, it means it is not available and we will return.

If the square is already visited then we will return.

Then we will check if the square is the ending point or not, if it is ending point then we can check the number of cells which are not being visited by the variable ```stepsRemaining```.

If stepsRemaining is equal to 0 then we can increment the variable ```totalNumberOfWays``` and then return.

We will mark the current square as visited and then call recursive function for all the four adjacent squares.

And don't forget to unmark the visited square.

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:

    vector<vector<int>> visited;
    int totalNumberOfWays = 0;

    // Recursive function for traversing all paths
    void findPaths(int row, int col, int stepsRemaining, vector<vector<int>> &grid){

        // Checking if the square is valid or not
        if(row < 0 || col < 0 || row == grid.size() || col == grid[0].size()){
            return;
        }

        // Checking whether the square is available or not
        if(grid[row][col] == -1 || visited[row][col] == 1){
            return;
        }

        // Base Case
        if(grid[row][col] == 2){
            // checking if the path covered all squares or not
            if(stepsRemaining == 0){
                totalNumberOfWays++;
            }
            return;
        }

        // Marking the square as visited
        visited[row][col] = 1;

        // Recursive Calls for all adjacent squares
        findPaths(row - 1, col, stepsRemaining - 1, grid);
        findPaths(row + 1, col, stepsRemaining - 1, grid);
        findPaths(row, col - 1, stepsRemaining - 1, grid);
        findPaths(row, col + 1, stepsRemaining - 1, grid);

        // Unmarking the square
        visited[row][col] = 0;

    }

    int uniquePathsIII(vector<vector<int>>& grid) {

        int m = grid.size();
        int n = grid[0].size();
        int x = 0;
        int y = 0;
        int totalSteps = 0;
        visited.resize(m, vector<int>(n, 0));

        // counting total number of available squares
        for(int i = 0; i < m; i++){
            for(int j = 0; j < n; j++){
                if(grid[i][j] == -1){
                    continue;
                }
                if(grid[i][j] == 1){
                    x = i;
                    y = j;
                }
                totalSteps++;
            }
        }

        findPaths(x, y, totalSteps - 1, grid);

        return totalNumberOfWays;

    }
};
```

In case of any queries, feel free to ask in the comment section.

If you like the explanation then please **upvote**. It took me a lot of efforts to write this article.

Thank you for reading till the end : )

