# Intuition and Approach
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
This initially looks like a hard problem , but trust me it is not.
Thanks to striver on YouTube for making DP on grids and 3D DP so easy to solve and understand.

Basically find the starting points of x and y using iteration and stop when grid[i][j]==1, because thats our starting point for the recursion, then call the recursive function, add the pretty simple base cases(one is out of bounds ,  and other one is if we reach the end) , then do the recursive calls for all 4 traversable directions.
*Note: dont forget to backtrack(yes i did forget initially :p)

Then just return the sum of all possibilities from the directions!
Yes, its that simple.
Additionally I have memoaized the solution by creating a DP array, you can tabulate your answer too but no one would expect tabulation or space optimization at on 3D DP(although both are simple to do)


Integer c basically here kinda checks how many nodes we have visited till now , so if the count of c is equal to empty then we can say that we have reached our destination(ofc destination node needs to be checked for being == 2 at first).
Instead of c one could have had used an additional function for checking if visited or not! Thats totally Upto you :D

