solutions.content:
**Explanation**:
1. Count totalSteps needed to reach dest using all valid blocks.
2. Also store start position, in the same loop.
3. Using recursive func, find the path to dest with steps == totalSteps.
4. Once found, don't end recursion completely here. Stop that branch only, then do backtracking and find new paths if available using the for loop of direction vector.

If you couldn't understand now, believe me, just go through the code once, it will become absolutely clear...

**Code**:
```
class Solution {
    int m, n;
    int totalSteps = 0;
    int count = 0;

    public int uniquePathsIII(int[][] grid) {
        m = grid.length;
        n = grid[0].length;

        int startX = -1, startY = -1;   

        for(int i = 0; i < m; i++)
            for(int j = 0; j < n; j++){
                if(grid[i][j] == 0 || grid[i][j] == 2)
                    totalSteps++;
                if(grid[i][j] == 1){
                    startX = i;
                    startY = j;
                } 
            }

        path(grid, startX, startY, 0);

        return count;
    }

    public void path(int[][] grid, int r, int c, int steps){

        if(steps == totalSteps && grid[r][c] == 2){
            count++;
            return;
        }

        if(grid[r][c] == 2)     // to stops path which pass through "2" twice & satisfying
            return;             // steps cond fianlly, & hence increasing count falsely.

		//Direction Vector
        int DIR[] = {0, -1, 0, 1, 0};
        for(int i = 0; i < 4; i++){
            int nr = r + DIR[i], nc = c + DIR[i+1];

            if(nr >= 0 && nr < m && nc >= 0 && nc < n && grid[nr][nc] != -1 && grid[nr][nc] != 1){
                steps++;
                if(grid[nr][nc] != 2)
                    grid[nr][nc] = -1;

                path(grid, nr, nc, steps);

                //backtracking lines: 
                steps--;
                if(grid[nr][nc] == -1)
                    grid[nr][nc] = 0;
            }
        }
    }
}
```

