# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
You're making a map of values and associating them with timestamps.

Since the timestamp inputs are always increasing, we don't have to worry about sorting or whatever.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Do the same thing as others, but instead of using a tuple, for every value we insert into the map for a key, create an object that tracks the biggest timestamp seen for this value.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$set()$$ is just insert into a map, so $$O(1)$$
$$get()$$ uses binary search in the event that the timestamp is less than $$max\_timestamp$$, so overall $$O(log\ n)$$

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
We make $$n$$ objects in the map, each of those objects will have at most $$2n$$ timestamps in memory at any given time (call to $$get()$$ makes another list)
Overall $$O(n)$$

