solutions.content:
I prefer using the hash table instead of array in this case to avoid checking the zeros
I am not sure why the question is tagged bit-manipulation though, doesn't seem we can do much with considering the individual bits

```
# Hash table solution
class Solution:
    # i, j, k can repeat
    # 0 <= nums[i] < 2^(16)
    # 2^16 isn't too big, and nums[i] & nums[j] would not go out of the range!
    # We can use an array to keep track of count of nums[i] & nums[j] first
    # Then for each nums[i], we & it against the current dp table
    def countTriplets(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:
        hash_table = {}
        n = len(nums)
        for i in range(n):
            for j in range(i,n):
                if nums[i] & nums[j] not in hash_table:
                    hash_table[nums[i] & nums[j]] = 0
                if i == j:
                    hash_table[nums[i]&nums[j]] += 1
                else:
                    hash_table[nums[i]&nums[j]] += 2

        result = 0
        for key in list(hash_table.keys()):
            for num in nums:
                if num & key == 0:
                    result += hash_table[key]

        return result
```

